Whether it be due to its associations with pink and purple, and subsequently, with women’s clothing, raspberry is perhaps one of the most unconventional colours in the realm of sartorialism. Where for most, it’s audacity acts as a repellent, for some, it presents an opportunity to differentiate. 
Cut from a lightweight blend of wool, linen and silk care of Loro Piana’s Proposte Giacche collection, the subtle textural nuances in the cloth offset its potentially abrasive richness.

Whilst fine tailoring always elevates a garment to new heights, quality artisanship is especially important when working with bright (and potentially distasteful) colours, lest the garment be nothing more than an insipid piece of showy garbage. Fortunately for Loro Piana’s and the client's sake, The Cloakroom’s Japanese artisans were able to imbue this jacket with the requisite taste-levels - both in terms of construction and its subtle accompaniments in the white shirt, grey tie and white pocket square. @thecloakroom
